  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Core Concepts</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Projects</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">Isolated workspaces where you organize agents, tasks, and resources.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="what-are-projects">What are Projects?</h2>
  <p>A project is the top-level organizational unit in Master of Puppets. It acts as an isolated workspace that contains everything needed to run an AI agent operation — roles, tasks, skills, and documents. All data is scoped to a project, so nothing leaks between workspaces.</p>
  <p>Think of a project as a self-contained company: it has its own org chart, its own objectives, its own knowledge base, and its own budget controls.</p>

  <h2 id="creating-a-project">Creating a Project</h2>
  <p>Every project needs a <strong>name</strong>. Once created, Master of Puppets automatically seeds it with:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Default role categories</strong> — pre-built department templates (Engineering, Research, Operations, etc.) so you can start staffing right away</li>
    <li><strong>Built-in skills</strong> — a library of reusable capabilities that agents can be equipped with</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You can switch between projects at any time. The currently active project determines what data you see across all screens.</p>

  <h2 id="multi-tenancy">Multi-tenancy</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets uses <code>Current.project</code> scoping for multi-tenancy. When you select a project, all queries — roles, tasks, documents — are automatically filtered to that project. This means you never accidentally see or modify another project's data.</p>
  <p>Models that belong to a project include the <code>Tenantable</code> concern, which enforces this scoping at the model level.</p>

  <h2 id="team-collaboration">Team Collaboration</h2>
  <p>Projects support multiple human users through <strong>memberships</strong>. Each membership has a role level:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Owner</strong> — full control, including destructive operations</li>
    <li><strong>Admin</strong> — can manage roles, tasks, and settings</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Invite collaborators to your project using the invitation system. Invitees receive a token-based link to accept and join.</p>

  <h2 id="concurrency-limits">Concurrency Limits</h2>
  <p>The <strong>max concurrent agents</strong> setting controls how many agents can run simultaneously within a project. When the limit is reached, new agent runs are <em>throttled</em> — queued and dispatched automatically as slots open up.</p>
  <p>Set this to <code>0</code> for unlimited concurrency. This is useful for development but in production you may want to cap it to control costs and system load.</p>

  <h2 id="project-defaults">Project Defaults</h2>
  <p>When a project is created, Master of Puppets seeds it with sensible defaults so you can get productive immediately:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Role categories</strong> — department templates with pre-written job specs that define what each category of agent does</li>
    <li><strong>Skills</strong> — built-in capabilities loaded from YAML definitions that can be attached to any role</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You can customize, add, or remove any of these defaults after creation.</p>

  <h2 id="emergency-stop">Emergency Stop</h2>
  <p>Every project has an <strong>emergency stop</strong> action that immediately halts all running agents. Use this when agents are behaving unexpectedly, exceeding budgets, or producing undesirable results. It terminates all active role runs across the project in a single action.</p>
</div>
